  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each of the following problems, consider the given relation <m>R</m> defined on a set <m>A</m>. Determine whether <m>R</m> satisfies any of the properties defined in Problem 4 above. If a property does not hold, say why.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>R = \{(a,a), (b,b), (c,c), (d,d), (a,b), (b,a)\}</m> on the set <m>A = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution component="w1s">
        <p>
          The relation is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive. Clearly it is not irreflexive. Moreover, <m>R</m> is not antisymmetric because there is a distinct pair of elements <m>a,b</m> where <m>a R b</m> and <m>b R a</m> are both true.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the relation defined on <m>A = \Z</m> as <m>x R y</m> if <m>|x-y|\lt1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution component="w1s">
        <p>
          Since <m>x,y \in \Z</m>, <m>xRy \iff |x-y|\lt1 \iff x=y</m>. Then this relation is clearly going to be reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the relation defined on <m>A = \Z</m> where we declare <m>x R y</m> if and only if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same parity.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution component="w1s">
        <p>
          This relation is reflexive because clearly <m>x</m> will have the same parity as itself, so <m>x R x</m>. Also, <m>R</m> is symmetric because if <m>xRy</m>, so <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same parity, then <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> will also have the same parity, so <m>yRx</m>. The relation is transitive because if <m>xRy</m> and <m>yRz</m>, then <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same parity and <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> have the same parity, so <m>x</m> and <m>z</m> thus have the same parity. Hence, <m>x R z</m>. (Notice that <m>R</m> is actually just congruence modulo 2.)
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
